mes]]&nbsp;- 2019\n*[[Bachar Houli]]&nbsp;- 2019\n{{Column}}\n\n'''[[AFL Coaches Association awards|AFL Coaches Association Champion Player of the Year]]'''\n*[[Trent Cotchin]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n*[[Dustin Martin]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n\n'''[[AFL Coaches Association awards|AFL Coaches Association Coach of the Year]]'''\n*[[Damien Hardwick]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n\n'''[[Leigh Matthews Trophy|AFL Players Association Most Valuable Player]]'''\n*[[Dustin Martin]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n\n'''[[International Rules Series|International Rules Series representatives]]'''\n<br/><span style=\"font-size:80%\">''Commenced 1998''</span>\n*[[Matthew Richardson (Australian rules footballer)|Matthew Richardson]]&nbsp;\u2013 1996, 1999, 2008\n*[[Wayne Campbell]]&nbsp;\u2013 1998, 1999, 2000\n*[[Andrew Kellaway]]&nbsp;\u2013 2000, 2002\n*[[Darren Gaspar]]&nbsp;\u2013 2001\n*[[Brad Ottens]]&nbsp;\u2013 2001\n*[[Joel Bowden]]&nbsp;\u2013 2001, 2004\n*[[Nathan G. Brown|Nathan Brown]]&nbsp;\u2013 2003, 2004\n*[[Brett Deledio]]&nbsp;\u2013 2005\n*[[Chris Newman (Australian rules footballer)|Chris Newman]]&nbsp;\u2013 2005\n*[[Andrew Raines]]&nbsp;\u2013 2006\n*[[Jack Riewoldt]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\n*[[Jake King]]&nbsp;\u2013 2011\n*[[Robin Nahas]]&nbsp;\u2013 2011\n\n'''[[22 Under 22 team|22 Under 22 team selection]]'''\n*[[Alex Rance]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n*[[Dustin Martin]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012, 2013\n*[[Trent Cotchin]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n*[[Brandon Ellis]]&nbsp;\u2013 2013, 2014, 2015\n*[[Daniel Rioli]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n*[[Jayden Short]]&nbsp;\u2013 2018\n*[[Dan Butler]]&nbsp;\u2013 2018\n*[[Sydney Stack]]&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n'''Club Best & Fairest'''\n:See [[Jack Dyer Medal]]\n\n'''Club leading goalkicker'''\n:See [[List of Michael Roach Medal recipients|Michael Roach Medal]]\n{{Columns-end}}\n\n==Reserves team==\nRichmond has had a [[Reserve team|reserves team]] participate in various competitions since the early 20th century. The reserves competition for the then-Victorian Football League (now trading as the [[Australian Football League]]) began in 1919 and the '''Richmond reserves''' recorded its first premiership in 1929. In the following 68 years, Richmond went on to win a further eight premierships in reserve-grade football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2013-12-04/history-of-the-richmond-reserves|title=History of the Richmond reserves|publisher=Richmondfc.com.au|date=4 Dec 2013|accessdate=11 Jan 2014}}</ref> The Richmond reserves participated in the VFL/AFL reserves, then the [[Victorian State Football League]] up to the 1999 season, then in the new [[Victorian Football League]] competition in [[2000 VFL season|2000]].\n\nIn 2001, the Richmond reserves team was dissolved and the club entered a [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|reserves affiliation]] with the [[Coburg Football Club]] in the VFL, using the latter as a feeder team. This arrangement lasted from 2001 until 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/un/aspirex/vfl_history.htm|title=VFL Genealogy (See year 2000)|publisher=Angelfire.com|date=|accessdate=11 Jan 2014}}</ref>\n\nRichmond ended the affiliation at the end of 2013, seeking to re-establish a more direct developmental structure by operating a stand-alone reserves team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/richmond-set-to-walk-away-from-coburg-in-2014/story-fnelctok-1226431540421|title=Richmond set to walk away from Coburg in 2014|publisher=HeraldSun.com.au|date=|accessdate=11 Jan 2014}}</ref> The reformed Richmond (VFL) reserves team has played in the VFL since 2014, playing its home games at the [[Punt Road Oval]], with many staged as [[curtain raisers]] to the club's senior home and away games at the nearby [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]].<ref>[http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2013-12-10/vfl-curtainraiser-bonanza-for-tigers VFL curtain-raiser bonanza for Tigers]</ref> The team is made up of a combination of senior listed AFL players, rookie listed players and VFL exclusive contracted players. The VFL exclusive player list is below. The team has won one VFL premiership since reforming.\n{{Richmond Football Club (reserves) current squad}}\n\n===Past premierships===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"6\"|'''Reserves Premierships (10)'''<ref>[http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2013-12-04/history-of-the-richmond-reserves History of the Richmond reserves]</ref>\n|-\n!Year \n!Competition\n!Opponent\n!Score\n!Venue\n|-\n| [[1929 VFL season|1929]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] || '''12.8 (80) - 7.15 (57)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1946 VFL season|1946]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] || '''7.15 (57) - 7.14 (56)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1954 VFL season|1954]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne]] || '''10.20 (80) - 4.9 (33)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1955 VFL season|1955]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]] || '''13.18 (96) - 9.12 (66)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1966 VFL season|1966]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] || '''14.11 (95) - 13.12 (90)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1971 VFL season|1971]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] || '''14.14 (98) - 8.18 (66)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1973 VFL season|1973]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] || '''17.18 (120) - 8.12 (60)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1977 VFL season|1977]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]] || '''19.18 (132) - 10.15 (75)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1997 AFL season|1997]] || [[Victorian State Football League|AFL Reserves (VSFL)]]|| [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] || '''17.12 (114) - 10.10 (70)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[2019 VFL season|2019]] || [[Victorian Football League|VFL]]|| [[Williamstown Football Club|Williamstown]] || '''8.10 (58) \u2013 7.13 (55)''' || [[Ikon Park]]\n|}\n\n===Best and fairest award===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year \n!Player\n!Award name\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Ross Young]] || Guinane Medal || VFL-only \n|-\n| 2015 || [[Matt Dea]]|| Guinane Medal || AFL listed \n|-\n| 2016 || [[Adam Marcon]]|| Guinane Medal || AFL listed \n|-\n| 2017 || [[Anthony Miles (Australian footballer)|Anthony Miles]]|| Guinane Medal || AFL listed\n|-\n| 2018 || [[Anthony Miles (Australian footballer)|Anthony Miles]]|| Guinane Medal || AFL listed\n|-\n| 2019 || Daniel Coffield || Guinane Medal || VFL-only \n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center; background: #ececec;\"|<small>Source:[https://www.tigerlandarchive.org/tiki-index.php?page=Reserves+Best+and+Fairest Tigerland Archive]. Last updated 1 October 2019</small>\n|}\n\n==Women's teams==\nThe Richmond Football Club has licenses for two women's teams, one team in the [[AFL Women's]] competition which  entered the league in 2020 and one team in the [[VFL Women's]] competition which was fielded for the first time in the 2018 VFLW season.\n\nThe program, including development pathways, is presently overseen by the women's football operations manager, [[Kate Sheahan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sheahan secures key Tiger job|url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2017-05-30/sheahan-secures-key-tiger-job|accessdate=10 November 2017|work=Richmond FC|publisher=Telstra Media|date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===History===\nRichmond has a thin history with women's football, with the club connected to just two women's matches in the 20th century. The first occurred in 1923, with a team dubbed the \"Tigresses\" playing off against the club's junior men's team (Cubs) as a fundraiser for a VFL team's interstate trip. As was the case with women versus men charity matches in that era, the men's team competed in the match in full fancy dress attire. In what was a non-serious affair the women's side (9.14 (68)) defeated the scoreless cubs side.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brunette Lenkic & Rob Hess|title=Play On! - The Hidden History of Women's Australian Rules Football|date=2016|publisher=Echo Publishing|location=Richmond, Victoria|isbn=9781760063160|page=49}}</ref> In August 1933, however, an all women's match was held between teams representing the suburbs of Richmond and Carlton in a charity match. While the Carlton team was associated with the club itself, Richmond did not pair with the side that played under its moniker. The match, played at Carlton's home ground, [[Princes Park (stadium)|Princes Park]], drew an estimated crowd of 10,000 and raised funds as part of a VFL bye-week carnival for the [[Royal Melbourne Hospital]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brunette Lenkic & Rob Hess|title=Play On! - The Hidden History of Women's Australian Rules Football|date=2016|publisher=Echo Publishing|location=Richmond, Victoria|isbn=9781760063160|page=77}}</ref>\n\n===AFL Women's team===\nIn 2016, Richmond was among 13 AFL clubs to bid for licenses to compete in the soon to be formed [[AFL Women's]] competition. The club was one of five to miss out, instead being awarded provisional licenses guaranteeing access in later expansions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Matthews|first1=Bruce|title=Eight teams named for inaugural women's league|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2016-06-15/eight-teams-named-for-inaugural-womens-league|accessdate=15 June 2016|work=AFL Media|publisher=[[Telstra Media]]|date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The following year they would again bid, this time winning the right to entry into the competition's fourth season, to be held in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Black|first1=Sarah|title=FAQ: The AFLW's expansion in 2019 and 2020|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-09-27/faq-the-aflws-expansion-in-2019-and-2020|accessdate=27 September 2017|work=AFL Media|publisher=[[Telstra Media]]|date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The club's first player signing came in the April 2019 expansion signing period, securing former {{AFLW WB}} captain [[Katie Brennan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Brennan a Tiger: Former Dogs' co-captain signs two-year deal|url=https://womens.afl/news/17771/brennan-a-tiger-former-dogs-co-captain-signs-two-year-deal|work=AFL Media|publisher=Telstra Media|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Current squad====\n{{Richmond AFL Women's current squad}}\n\n====Season summaries====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | Richmond AFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2020 AFL Women's season|2020]]\n|14th ^\n|[[Tom Hunter (coach)|Tom Hunter]]\n|[[Katie Brennan]]\n|TBC\n|[[Courtney Wakefield]] (4)\n|}\n<small>^ Denotes the ladder was split into two or more conferences. Figure refers to the club's overall finishing position that season.</small>\n\n===VFL Women's team===\nIn October 2017, Richmond was granted a license to field a team in the 2018 VFL Women's season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Richmond secures VFLW licence|url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2017-10-11/richmond-secures-vflw-licence|accessdate=10 November 2017|work=Richmond FC|publisher=Telstra Media|date=11 October 2017}}</ref> They are to be one of 13 clubs in the competition, including all 10 Victorian-based AFL clubs. The league operates in the winter season (separately to the AFLW competition), with players not contractually bound to play for the same clubs in both leagues.\n\nFormer men's VFL assistant coach Tom Hunter was named the team's head coach in November 2017. He is additionally responsible for overseeing the women's arm of the club's Next Generation Academy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tigers appoint inaugural VFLW coach|url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2017-11-10/tigers-appoint-inaugural-vflw-coach|accessdate=10 November 2017|work=Richmond FC|publisher=Telstra Media|date=10 November 2017}}</ref> [[Jess Kennedy]] was named the team's inaugural captain in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cahill|first1=Georgina|title=VFLW leadership group|url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2018-05-04/vflw-leadership-group|accessdate=4 May 2018|work=Richmond FC|publisher=Telstra Media}}</ref>\n\n====Current squad====\n{{Rls\n|squadname=Richmond Football Club (VFLW)\n|templatename=\n|BC1      =black; border: solid #FED102 2px\n|FC1      =#FED102;\n|BC2      =black; border: solid #FED102 2px\n|FC2      =#FED102;\n|source   =[https://vfl.com.au/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/05/All-2019-VFL-Womens-squad-lists.pdf List]\n|date     =10 May 2019\n|column1_title=Playing list\n|list1a={{Rls player|no=&nbsp;1|name=[[Jess Kennedy]] '''(c)'''}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;2|name=[[Phoebe Monahan]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;3|name=[[Katie Brennan]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;4|name=[[Monique Conti]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;5|name=[[Maddy Brancatisano]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;7|name=[[Lauren Tesoriero]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;8|name=Jacqueline Graham}}\n*{{Rls player|no=&nbsp;9|name=[[Hannah Burchell]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=11|name=Alice Edmonds}}\n*{{Rls player|no=12|name=[[Laura Bailey (footballer)|Laura Bailey]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=13|name=Alana Woodward}}\n*{{Rls player|no=14|name=[[Sabrina Frederick]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=15|name=Rebecca Miller}}\n*{{Rls player|no=16|name=Courtney Wakefield}}\n*{{Rls player|no=17|name=Emma Gunn}}\n*{{Rls player|no=18|name=Lisa Davie}}\n*{{Rls player|no=19|name=Kate Dempsey}}\n*{{Rls player|no=20|name=Hannah McLaren}}\n*{{Rls player|no=22|name=Shayla Marsh}}\n*{{Rls player|no=23|name=Tamara Smith}}\n\n|list2a={{Rls player|no=24|name=Tayla Stahl-Smith}}\n*{{Rls player|no=25|name=Grace Egan}}\n*{{Rls player|no=26|name=Evelyn Burry}}\n*{{Rls player|no=28|name=Gabrielle Seymour}}\n*{{Rls player|no=29|name=Kodi Jacques}}\n*{{Rls player|no=30|name=Dalia Edward}}\n*{{Rls player|no=32|name=Imogen Milford}}\n*{{Rls player|no=33|name=Jenna Colwell}}\n*{{Rls player|no=34|name=[[Akec Makur Chuot]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=35|name=Natarsha Bamblett}}\n*{{Rls player|no=36|name=Emily Paterno}}\n*{{Rls player|no=37|name=Millie Kilngbeil}}\n*{{Rls player|no=39|name=Mel Lindsay}}\n*{{Rls player|no=41|name=[[Sarah Last]]}}\n*{{Rls player|no=43|name=Grace Campbell}}\n*{{Rls player|no=45|name=Rachel Poke}}\n*{{Rls player|no=46|name=Hannah Ibrahim}}\n*{{Rls player|no=52|name=Maddy Baldwin}}\n*{{Rls player|no=54|name=Jordyn Jolliffe}}\n\n|coach=Tom Hunter\n|assistant=\n}}\n\n====Season summaries====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | Richmond VFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2018\n|12th \n|[[Tom Hunter (coach)|Tom Hunter]]\n|[[Jess Kennedy|Jessica Kennedy]]\n|[[Jess Kennedy|Jessica Kennedy]]\n|[[Kate Dixon]] (9)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2019\n|4th\n|[[Tom Hunter (coach)|Tom Hunter]]\n|[[Jess Kennedy|Jessica Kennedy]]\n|[[Monique Conti]] \n|[[Tayla Stahl]] (19)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2020\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|TBC \n|TBC\n|}\n<small>Sources: [https://vfl.com.au/richmond-womens-historical-data/ Club historical data] and [http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-118-0-518546-0&pool=1001&round=0&a=STATS VFLW stats]</small>\n\n==Wheelchair football==\nRichmond has had a team compete in the [[Wheelchair Australian rules football|Victorian Wheelchair Football League]] since its inception in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=New AFL wheelchair league to launch in 2018 featuring Collingwood, Essendon, Hawthorn, Richmond and St Kilda |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/more-news/new-afl-wheelchair-league-to-launch-in-2018-featuring-collingwood-essendon-hawthorn-richmond-and-st-kilda/news-story/38724cf69fa31d90aa91c00c9b7ffa15 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=Herald Sun |publisher=News Corp Australia |date=16 March 2018}}</ref> The team were runners up in 2018 before winning the league premiership in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spiteri |first1=Tate |title=VWFL Tigers clinch premiership |url=https://www.richmondfc.com.au/news/2019-09-02/vwfl-tigers-clinch-premiership |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=Richmond FC |publisher=Telstra Media |date=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"6\"|'''Wheelchair Premierships (1)'''\n|-\n!Year \n!Competition\n!Opponent\n!Score\n!Venue\n|-\n| 2019 || Victorian Wheelchair Football League|| [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] || '''9.7 (61) - 7.5 (47)''' || Boroondara Sports Complex\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Australia}}\n*[[List of Richmond Football Club seasons]]\n*[[List of Richmond Football Club players]]\n*[[List of Richmond Football Club coaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*Blainey, G: ''A Game of Our Own: The Origins of Australian Football'', Melbourne 1990\n*Hansen, B: ''Tigerland'', Richmond Past Players and Officials Assoc, Melbourne 1992\n*Hogan, P: ''The Tigers Of Old'', Richmond FC, Melbourne 1996\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070317035606/http://www.richmondfc.com.au/TheClub/History/HallofFame/tabid/7638/Default.aspx Richmond Football Club \u2013 Hall of Fame]\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.richmondfc.com.au/}}\n{{Commons category|Richmond Football Club (Australian football)|Richmond Football Club}}\n\n{{Richmond Football Club}}\n{{VFL/AFL minor premiers}}\n{{VFL/AFL premiers}}\n{{Australian Football League}}\n{{AFL Women's}}\n{{VFL}}\n{{VFL Women's}}\n{{Melbourne Sports Teams}}\n\n[[Category:Aus